# Review & PR Checklist — run against your own diff

When you've finished editing UI, run this list **against your own
changes** before ending your reply. Tick honestly. If a box can't be
ticked, explain why in your `Design-system decisions:` block — do not
tick it anyway.

## Reuse

- [ ] Searched `packages/ui/src/components/{primitives,patterns}` before
      adding any new component.
- [ ] If a near-match existed, extended its variants instead of forking.
- [ ] New components are at the right tier (L1 / L2 / L3) per
      `01-ux-ui-system.mdc`.

## Tokens & styling

- [ ] No raw hex / `px` / `rgb()` / `hsl()` / inline `style={}` outside
      L1 primitives.
- [ ] No Tailwind default palette (`gray-*`, `red-*`, `blue-*`, …) in
      new code.
- [ ] No arbitrary Tailwind values (`text-[14px]`, `bg-[#...]`,
      `p-[18px]`).
- [ ] If a token was added: `tokens.json` updated → `npm run
      tokens:generate` run → `design-system/tokens/README.md` updated →
      `changelog.md` entry added.

## Semantic HTML & a11y

- [ ] Uses `<button>` / `<a>` / `<input>` / `<dialog>` etc., not
      `<div>`/`<span>` with handlers.
- [ ] Every interactive element has an accessible name (visible label
      or `aria-label`).
- [ ] Keyboard reachable in visual order; Enter/Space activate buttons.
- [ ] Visible focus ring on every interactive element (no
      `outline-none` without replacement).
- [ ] Touch targets ≥ 44×44 on touch viewports.
- [ ] Form inputs use `FormField` (or another L1 control). No bare
      `<input>` in feature code.
- [ ] Errors carry a non-color signal (icon or label) and are
      announced (`role="alert"`).
- [ ] Animations branch on `useReducedMotion()` when > 200ms or
      involving translation.
- [ ] Live regions (`aria-live`) on changing data (timers, set
      counters, async results).

## Responsive

- [ ] Mobile-first: default styles target `<sm`; breakpoints add up.
- [ ] Verified at `375 × 667`, `768 × 1024`, `1280 × 800`.
- [ ] No horizontal scroll except intentional carousels.
- [ ] Bottom-pinned primary actions clear the iOS home indicator on
      full-bleed screens.
- [ ] In-session UI stays legible in landscape on phones.
- [ ] Hover-only affordances have a touch equivalent (long-press / kebab
      menu).

## Content

- [ ] Sentence case on buttons, labels, headings.
- [ ] Button labels are verb phrases that name the outcome ("Save
      changes", not "OK").
- [ ] Errors say what went wrong **and** what to do.
- [ ] Numbers use `tabular-nums`; weights, time, currency per
      `content-guidelines.md`.

## States

- [ ] Loading, empty, error, loaded states all exist for any fetch
      surface.
- [ ] Async triggers disable + show progress within 100ms.
- [ ] Destructive actions confirm via dialog, not toast.

## Code hygiene

- [ ] No `console.log` (warn/error allowed).
- [ ] No `@ts-ignore` without a comment explaining why.
- [ ] No new dependencies — wrap or extend instead.
- [ ] Imports follow the order rule (builtin → external → internal →
      parent → sibling).
- [ ] `npm run lint`, `typecheck`, `tokens:check` would pass.

## PR description (for the human running PR)

- [ ] UI checklist filled in (the GitHub PR template carries this).
- [ ] Light + dark screenshots, mobile + desktop attached.
- [ ] Figma frame linked.
- [ ] Changelog entry if the system changed.

## Output format — Design-system decisions

Every UI reply ends with this section. Use this exact shape:

```
Design-system decisions:
- Reused: <component> from @famm/ui (path: …)
- Tokens: <list> (intent if non-obvious)
- A11y: <what was preserved or added>
- Responsive: <what was verified>
- OPEN: <anything you weren't sure about, with a specific question>
```

Keep it tight — three to six bullets, one line each. The reviewer reads
this to decide what they need to verify manually.

## When you can't tick a box

Say so. Examples:

- "Could not verify dark-mode contrast — please run `--theme=dark` and
  confirm the `text-text-muted / surface-sunken` pair."
- "OPEN: rest-timer hits 44×44 on phones but only 40×40 on the
  detail-list quick-edit. Worth a follow-up?"

Honesty here saves a round-trip in review.
